az aks create \
  --resource-group myResourceGroup \
  --name myAKSCluster \
  --node-count 3 \
  --network-plugin azure \
  --vnet-subnet-id /subscriptions/<sub-id>/resourceGroups/<rg>/providers/Microsoft.Network/virtualNetworks/<vnet>/subnets/<subnet> \
  --service-cidr 10.0.0.0/16 \
  --dns-service-ip 10.0.0.10

1. az aks create
This is the Azure CLI command to create a new AKS cluster.
2. --resource-group myResourceGroup
Specifies the Azure Resource Group that will contain your AKS cluster and related resources.
If the resource group doesn't exist, you must create it beforehand (az group create ...).
3. --name myAKSCluster
Sets the name for your new AKS cluster.
4. --node-count 3
The cluster will start with 3 worker nodes (VMs) in its default node pool.
These nodes will run your Kubernetes workloads (like pods and services).
5. --network-plugin azure
Specifies that the cluster should use the Azure CNI (Container Networking Interface) for networking.
With Azure CNI, each pod gets an IP address from the Azure VNet, making network management more flexible and integrated with Azure resources.
6. --vnet-subnet-id ...
Tells AKS to deploy the cluster's nodes inside a specific subnet of an existing Azure Virtual Network (VNet).
This allows the cluster to communicate privately with other Azure resources (like databases, VMs) and supports advanced networking.
7. --service-cidr 10.0.0.0/16
Defines the IP address range for Kubernetes services (like ClusterIP/LoadBalancer services).
This CIDR block must NOT overlap with your VNet's subnet IP range!
8. --dns-service-ip 10.0.0.10
Sets the internal IP address used for the Kubernetes DNS service (CoreDNS).
Must be an IP address within the range specified by --service-cidr.


Summary Table
Parameter	Purpose
--resource-group	Azure Resource Group for the cluster
--name	Name of the AKS cluster
--node-count	Number of worker nodes (VMs) in the cluster
--network-plugin	Networking model used (Azure CNI in this case)
--vnet-subnet-id	Subnet where AKS nodes/pods will be deployed
--service-cidr	IP range for Kubernetes service VIPs
--dns-service-ip	IP address for CoreDNS service inside the cluster

When to Use This Command?
When setting up a new AKS cluster for the first time.
When you need custom networking—such as VNet integration, specific service IP ranges, or Azure CNI plugin.
Use it in automation scripts, DevOps pipelines, or direct CLI setup.
What Happens After Running?
Azure will:
Set up a managed Kubernetes control plane for you.
Provision 3 VMs in your specified subnet for worker nodes.
Configure networking as per your settings.
Reserve service and DNS IP ranges inside the cluster for Kubernetes operations.

This command is used at the AKS cluster creation stage to set up the baseline cluster with custom networking (Azure CNI, VNet/subnet, service IP space), node count, and naming—all in a single step.

