What Does --service-cidr 10.0.0.0/16 Do in AKS?
The --service-cidr parameter defines the IP address range that Kubernetes will use to assign virtual IPs (VIPs) to Kubernetes Services within your AKS cluster.

These IPs are used ONLY for Kubernetes services (such as ClusterIP, LoadBalancer, and NodePort).
They are not used for pods or nodes.
🗂️ How Service IPs Work
When a new Kubernetes Service is created (for example, when you expose a deployment with a service), Kubernetes will assign a virtual IP (VIP) to that service from the range you specify here.
Example:
If your --service-cidr is 10.0.0.0/16, your services might get addresses like 10.0.0.42, 10.0.0.100, etc.
Important:

This range should NOT overlap with other ranges such as your Virtual Network subnet or the pod CIDR range.

Does this Assign IPs to Nodes or Pods?
Nodes:
Assigned IPs from the Azure VNet subnet you specify with --vnet-subnet-id.
Pods:
With Azure CNI plugin (--network-plugin azure), pods get IPs from the same subnet as the nodes (VNet subnet).
With Kubenet plugin, pods get IPs from a separate, non-overlapping CIDR specified using --pod-cidr.
Services:
Assigned IPs from the Service CIDR (--service-cidr).
🔹 So, --service-cidr ONLY affects service VIPs—not pod or node IPs.

What Happens If the Service CIDR Range Runs Out of IP Addresses?
If you create a very large number of Services (hundreds/thousands) so that every IP in the service CIDR is used, no new Service VIPs can be assigned.
New services will fail to get an IP, and you'll see errors such as:
"Failed to assign an IP address to service: no available IPs in the Service CIDR range."

What to Do If Service IPs Are Exhausted?

Best Practice:

Plan ahead and assign a sufficiently large CIDR for services when you create the AKS cluster.
/16 (as in your example) provides ~65,000 IPs for services (usually more than enough for most clusters).

If Already Out of IPs:

Unfortunately, the --service-cidr range CANNOT be changed after cluster creation in AKS.
Only solution: Create a new cluster with a larger service CIDR, and migrate workloads.


In Short
--service-cidr 10.0.0.0/16 assigns the range for service (VIP) IPs only.
It will not affect pods or nodes.
If exhausted, only solution is to recreate the cluster with a larger range—so plan accordingly!




Why Would IP Exhaustion Happen?
Subnet is too small: Not enough addresses allocated for the number of nodes * max pods per node.
You scale out node count or pod density: New IPs are needed for each.
Other Azure resources share the subnet (VMs, other services).
Example:

You have a /24 subnet (256 addresses), AKS reserves some for Azure infra, then allocates the rest to nodes and pods.
If you deploy many pods or add many nodes, the IP pool runs out and new pods cannot be scheduled.
What Happens When You Exhaust Subnet IPs?
New pods cannot be scheduled and will remain in Pending state.
Errors such as “Failed to allocate pod IP” occur.
App deployment in your cluster is blocked.
How Do You Prevent IP Exhaustion?

Plan Subnet Size Upfront

For Azure CNI, make your subnet much larger than you think you need.
Microsoft recommends a /23, /22, or larger (/16 for large clusters), depending on planned scaling.

Calculate Needed IPs

Formula: (number of nodes) x (max pods per node) + node count + buffer
Default max pods per node is 30 (can be increased).

Use Separate Subnets

If possible, have a dedicated subnet for AKS nodes/pods, not shared with other Azure resources.

Tune Max Pods Per Node

Can be set when creating node pool (--max-pods). Affects how many pod IPs are reserved per node.


Remediation: What to Do if You Hit Exhaustion?
1. Resize Subnet (If Possible)
If the subnet doesn’t have other dependencies, expand it in Azure Portal, CLI, or PowerShell.
2. Add a New Node Pool in a Larger Subnet
Create a new subnet with a larger address space.
Add a new node pool in that subnet.
Migrate workloads to the new pool.
3. Resize the Cluster (Create New One)
For severe/complicated cases, create a new AKS cluster with a larger subnet and migrate workloads via backup/restore, manifests, or Helm.
4. Use Kubenet (if advanced features aren’t needed)
Only requires node IPs; pods get overlay addresses, resulting in much lower VNet IP consumption.
Typical Error Messages:
PodPending: Failed to assign an IP address to pod
There are no available IP addresses in the subnet for this AKS cluster
